<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="41" pageNumber="40">
Diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">Hypostomus pagei</taxonomicName>
differs from most other members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group mainly in coloration: a light, gray-brown with the spots considerably faded or absent (vs. a deep, dark brown with the spots well-developed). Juvenile 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">H. pagei</taxonomicName>
additionally have the caudal fin darkest along both spines and at the base, clear medially (Fig. 14B), a color pattern not found in any other members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">Hypostomus pagei</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hondae">H. hondae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="plecostomoides">H. plecostomoides</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">Hypostomus pagei</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hondae">H. hondae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="plecostomoides">H. plecostomoides</taxonomicName>
by the general absence of spots on the caudal fin and/or caudal-fin spines (
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">H. pagei</taxonomicName>
may have some very faint spots on the caudal-fin spines; some 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="plecostomoides">H. plecostomoides</taxonomicName>
lack spots on the caudal-fin spines, but the spines are almost black instead of light gray-brown) and by having shorter pectoral-fin spines (reaching 0-1 plates beyond pelvic fin when depressed below the pelvic fin vs. 2-3 plates with the exception of one specimen of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">H. pagei</taxonomicName>
that has pectoral-fin spines that reach two plates beyond the pelvic fin and the one specimen of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="plecostomoides">H. plecostomoides</taxonomicName>
examined from the Lago Valencia drainage that has pectoral-fin spines that do not reach beyond the pelvic fin).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="41">
Description: See description of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">Hypostomus cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group for more details. Morphometric data given in Table 4. Color gray-brown. Spots, if present, usually very faint and restricted to paired fins, dorsal fin, head, anterior part of body and/or abdomen. Spots particularly faint in adults. Caudal fin darkest distomedially. Spots absent from entire caudal fin in adults. Juveniles with faint spots on caudal-fin spines and dark brown along spines and base (Fig. 14B). Caudal fin coloration darker than body color in juveniles, lightens ontogenetically until equal to body color. Juveniles typically slightly darker overall than adults.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="41">
Dorsal fin short, falling short of preadipose plate. Depressed pectoral-fin spine ventral to pelvic fin reaches beyond bases of pelvic-fin rays, but to a lesser extent than in other species of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group (0-1 plate vs. 2-3 plates in most other specimens of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="41">Keels weak, almost absent. Orbits forming slight ridge slightly raised above medial surface of head; ridges of dorsal and lateral aspect of head fairly smooth. Longitudinal ridge formed of raised bone and slightly larger odontodes absent on pterotic-supracleithrum beginning at postdorsal corner of orbit. Opercle usually broadly exposed, always supporting much more than ten odontodes. Plates in skin anterior to dorsal-fin spine absent or few (Fig. 6A; Table 7).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="41">Each jaw with 7-17 teeth (mode = 11), teeth large and spoon-shaped. Average angle between dentaries 63° (SD = 5°; range: 53°-73°; N=14). Lateral line plates 27-29; dorsal plates 8-9; interdorsal plates 6-8; adipose caudal plates 9-10.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="41">
Range: Found in northwestern Venezuela in the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Aroa, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Tocuyo, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Yaracuy basins, short rivers that drain directly into Caribbean Sea (Fig. 11). 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8E17BFCB-CFC3-4096-8202-76C9E23D3D1F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus pagei Armbruster 2003:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pagei">Hypostomus pagei</taxonomicName>
is allopatric to all other species of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="41">Etymology: Named for Dr. Lawrence M. Page for his help and guidance during my career, and to honor the fact that he helped to collect a majority of the specimens of this species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
